\cb2 Arb . Oaths are but words , and words are air . Oh ! precious mum\cb1 \
\cb2 mery !\cb1 \
\cb2 Clo . Stand from the statue , Guards .\cb1 \
\cb2 [ Two GUARDS , who have been standing before statue , with banners , withdraw each side , and discover NYDIA on the pedestal .\cb1 \
\cb2 Arb . Nydia , wherefore art thou here ?\cb1 \
\cb2 Nydia . To right the innocent and condemn the guilty . Mighty Pr\'e6- tor , I cannot see thee , yet I know by free air playing on my cheek , that I am standing in the arena . Thou sittest there as a judge of equity . Glaucus is innocent - most innocent , I swear !\cb1 \
\cb2 Clo . Speak out , and fear not .\cb1 \
\cb2 Nydia . The hand ensanguined in Apacides ' blood , is Arbaces ' own . Clo . What says Arbaces to this charge ?\cb1 \
\cb2 Arb . In sooth , Lord Clodius , nothing . I am descended from a noble race of kings , and cannot stoop to make answer to a blind flower - girl's cunning . Shame on thee , Clodius ! Methinks it will sound well in Rome , that the Pompeian Pr\'e6tor stopped the games , because a flower- girl bid him .\cb1 \
\cb2 Nydia Hard - hearted man ! Dost thou not fear that mercy thou de- niest to others , will , at the last day , be denied thee ? Pr\'e6tor , I have a witness - may he be summoned ?\cb1 \
\cb2 Clo . Name him .\cb1 \
\cb2 Nydia . Calenus .\cb1 \
\cb2 Clo . Go seek him .\cb1 \
\cb2 [ Exit OFFICER , I ..\cb1 \
\cb2 Arb . [ Aside . ] Calenus ? -- why that is false . I plunged him deep into a dungeon , from which no sound could escape , and ere this he is dead . Pr\'e6tor , ' tis stooping from my high estate to vouchsafe any answer to this charge ; but , since the public crowd have heard the lie , let them claim its punishment . I , Arbaces the Egyptian , do declare Calenus absent on a message from the temple - forest , and hills , and leagues of raging sea are now between us ; and I charge you , Pr\'e6tor , on your office , to doom this girl to the punishinent she merits . [ As ARBACES turns to L. , CALENUS enters chord . ] Do spectres walk ? -will not the earth inclose thee ? - Hence ! thou hast no business here ! - What ! -still there ? Living or dead , spectre or man , know that Arbaces is thy foe ! [ He draws his sword to rush on CALENUS - the guards stop him . ] Ha ! you think you have me in the toils ; but he that binds the lion must needs be strong ! -Say that I did this murder - that I spilt the puddle of his youthful blood - ' twas a greater honor so to die than any ye were born to . What ho , my guards ! -Pompeian nobles and Pompeian slaves , Arbaces does defy ye !\cb1 \
\cb2 [ At this moment , the fire breaks forth from the mountain , and the walls of arena fall - everybody cries , The earthquake the earth- quake ! -ARBACES is killed by the falling of statue - all in confu sion and screams till curtain falls on a grand tableau .\cb1 \
